ce:section.ce:para:
Zante et al. [9] have reported that because of the affinity of decanoic acid for the transition metal ions, the extraction of these metal ions using a DES made of lidocaine and decanoic acid appeared as a very efficient one [43]. This DES exhibits poor ability to extract less than 30 % of lithium from chloride media [44]. Therefore,use of this DES could be effective for the separation of transition metals from lithium. The separation process is based on the difference in the oxidation states of transition metal ions and Li(I). With this background in this work the separation possibility of Ni/Co/Li employing this Ali:HexA DES in kerosene has been explored. It was observed that the extraction of Ni(II) using DES (Ali:HexA) in kerosene proved as highly effective as compare to other two metal ions. From these visual observations (green colour) it is clear that Ni(II) gets extracted to the DES-kerosene phase leaving behind Li(I) and Co(II) in the raffinate (Fig. 14
                           ). Photographs of Ali:HexA DES, Ali:HexA DES diluted with kerosene, prepared aqueous phase prior to extraction, after extraction are given in the Fig. 15
                           .
